146. charybdim, Scyllam. Two monsters who gave their names to two rocks situated in the straits between Italy and Sicily ; they were both formidable to sassors, the former being said to swallow down the waters of the sea thrice a day, and thrice throw them up again; the latter was represented as surrounded by fierce hounds, hence C.’s allusion in ‘ canibus,’ by which he means of course the ‘monsters' in the retinue of Verres.
